<p><strong>Broad-footed Mole (<em>Scapanus latimanus)</em></strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Talpidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Scapanus latimanus</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong>Broad-footed Mole (aka California Mole)<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p>The Broad-footed mole is 5-6 inches in body length, has a 1½-inch tail, and weighs about 2 ounces. Its front feet are broad, its nose naked, nostrils open upward, is blackish brown to black in color, and has a slightly haired tail. For a more detailed overview of this species see 〔<a href="http://www.enature.com/fieldguides/detail.asp?shapeID=1034&amp;curGroupID=5&amp;lgfromWhere=&amp;curPageNum=17" target="_blank">eNature</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>This creature occurs in porous soils in valleys and meadows in mountains. It bears 2-5 young between March-April once a year. It rarely comes aboveground; feeds on insects, earthworms, and other small invertebrates. In captivity it can eat 63-107 percent of its own weight in earthworms.</p>
